# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: map-projections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] A **geographic coordinate system** (**GCS**) is a spherical or geodetic coordinate system for measuring and communicating positions directly on Earth as latitude and longitude.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] It is the simplest, oldest, and most widely used type of the various spatial reference systems that are in use, and forms the basis for most others.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Although latitude and longitude form a coordinate tuple like a Cartesian coordinate system, geographic coordinate systems are not Cartesian because the measurements are angles and are not on a planar surface.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] A full GCS specification, such as those listed in the EPSG and ISO 19111 standards, also includes a choice of geodetic datum (including an Earth ellipsoid), as different datums will yield different latitude and longitude values for the same location.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The invention of a geographic coordinate system is generally credited to Eratosthenes of Cyrene, who composed his now-lost *Geography* at the Library of Alexandria in the 3rd century BC.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] A century later, Hipparchus of Nicaea improved on this system by determining latitude from stellar measurements rather than solar altitude and determining longitude by timings of lunar eclipses, rather than dead reckoning.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy credited him with the full adoption of longitude and latitude, rather than measuring latitude in terms of the length of the midsummer day.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Ptolemy's 2nd-century *Geography* used the same prime meridian but measured latitude from the Equator instead.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] After their work was translated into Arabic in the 9th century, Al-Khwārizmī's *Book of the Description of the Earth* corrected Marinus' and Ptolemy's errors regarding the length of the Mediterranean Sea, causing medieval Arabic cartography to use a prime meridian around 10° east of Ptolemy's line.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Mathematical cartography resumed in Europe following Maximus Planudes' recovery of Ptolemy's text a little before 1300; the text was translated into Latin at Florence by Jacopo d'Angelo around 1407.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] In 1884, the United States hosted the International Meridian Conference, attended by representatives from twenty-five nations.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Twenty-two of them agreed to adopt the longitude of the Royal Observatory in Greenwich, England as the zero-reference line.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The Dominican Republic voted against the motion, while France and Brazil abstained.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] France adopted Greenwich Mean Time in place of local determinations by the Paris Observatory in 1911.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The *latitude* φ of a point on Earth's surface is defined in one of three ways, depending on the type of coordinate system.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] In each case, the latitude is the angle formed by the plane of the equator and a line formed by the point on the surface and a second point on equatorial plane.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The path that joins all points of the same latitude traces a circle on the surface of Earth, as viewed from above the north or south pole, called parallels, as they are parallel to the equator and to each other.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The north pole is 90° N; the south pole is 90° S.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The 0° parallel of latitude is defined to be the equator, the fundamental plane of a geographic coordinate system.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The equator divides the globe into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The *longitude* λ of a point on Earth's surface is the angle east or west of a reference meridian to another meridian that passes through that point.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] All meridians are halves of great ellipses, which converge at the North and South Poles.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The meridian of the British Royal Observatory in Greenwich, in southeast London, England, is the international prime meridian, although some organizations—such as the French Institut national de l'information géographique et forestière—continue to use other meridians for internal purposes.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The antipodal meridian of Greenwich is both 180°W and 180°E.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] This is not to be conflated with the International Date Line, which partly overlaps with the 180° meridian but diverges from it in several places for political and convenience reasons, including between far eastern Russia and the far western Aleutian Islands.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The combination of these two components specifies the position of any location on the surface of Earth, without consideration of altitude or depth.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The visual grid on a map formed by lines of latitude and longitude is known as a *graticule*.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The origin/zero point of this system is located in the Gulf of Guinea about 625 km (390 mi) south of Tema, Ghana, a location often facetiously called Null Island.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] In order to use the theoretical definitions of latitude, longitude, and height to precisely measure actual locations on the physical earth, a *geodetic datum* must be used.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] A *horizonal datum* is used to precisely measure latitude and longitude, while a *vertical datum* is used to measure elevation or altitude.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Both types of datum bind a mathematical model of the shape of the earth (usually a reference ellipsoid for a horizontal datum, and a more precise geoid for a vertical datum) to the earth.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Traditionally, this binding was created by a network of control points, surveyed locations at which monuments are installed, and were only accurate for a region of the surface of the Earth.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Newer datums are based on a global network for satellite measurements (GNSS, VLBI, SLR and DORIS).
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] This combination of a mathematical model and physical binding ensures that users of the same datum obtain identical coordinates for a given physical point.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] However, different datums typically produce different coordinates for the same location (sometimes deviating several hundred meters) not due to actual movement, but because the reference system itself is shifted.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Because any spatial reference system or map projection is ultimately calculated from latitude and longitude, it is crucial that they clearly state the datum on which they are based.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] For example, a UTM coordinate based on a WGS84 realisation will be different than a UTM coordinate based on NAD27 for the same location.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Transforming coordinates from one datum to another requires a datum transformation method such as a Helmert transformation, although in certain situations a simple translation may be sufficient.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums may be global, meaning that they represent the whole Earth, or they may be regional, meaning that they represent an ellipsoid best-fit to only a portion of the Earth.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Datums with a regional fit of the ellipsoid that are chosen by a national cartographical organization include the North American Datums, the European ED50, and the British OSGB36.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Given a location, the datum provides the latitude $\phi$ and longitude $\lambda$ .
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] In the United Kingdom there are three common latitude, longitude, and height systems in use.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] WGS 84 differs at Greenwich from the one used on published maps OSGB36 by approximately 112 m.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Points on the Earth's surface move relative to each other due to continental plate motion, subsidence, and diurnal Earth tidal movement caused by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] This daily movement can be as much as a meter.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Continental movement can be up to 10 cm a year, or 10 m in a century.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] A weather system high-pressure area can cause a sinking of 5 mm.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Scandinavia is rising by 1 cm a year as a result of the melting of the ice sheets of the last ice age, but neighboring Scotland is rising by only 0.2 cm.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] These changes are insignificant if a regional datum is used, but are statistically significant if a global datum is used.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] On the GRS 80 or WGS 84 spheroid at sea level at the Equator, one latitudinal second measures 30.715 m, one latitudinal minute is 1843 m and one latitudinal degree is 110.6 km.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The circles of longitude, meridians, meet at the geographical poles, with the west–east width of a second naturally decreasing as latitude increases.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] On the Equator at sea level, one longitudinal second measures 30.92 m, a longitudinal minute is 1855 m and a longitudinal degree is 111.3 km.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The returned measure of meters per degree latitude varies continuously with latitude.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] The formulae both return units of meters per degree.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] ( $\textstyle {\beta }\,\!$ is known as the reduced (or parametric) latitude).
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Aside from rounding, this is the exact distance along a parallel of latitude; getting the distance along the shortest route will be more work, but those two distances are always within 0.6 m of each other if the two points are one degree of longitude apart.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] Like any series of multiple-digit numbers, latitude-longitude pairs can be challenging to communicate and remember.
[src:map-projections/geographic-coordinate-system] These are not distinct coordinate systems, only alternative methods for expressing latitude and longitude measurements.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In cartography, a **map projection** is any of a broad set of transformations employed to represent the curved two-dimensional surface of a globe on a plane.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In a map projection, coordinates, often expressed as latitude and longitude, of locations from the surface of the globe are transformed to coordinates on a plane.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Projection is a necessary step in creating a two-dimensional map and is one of the essential elements of cartography.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] All projections of a sphere on a plane necessarily distort the surface in some way.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Depending on the purpose of the map, some distortions are acceptable and others are not; therefore, different map projections exist in order to preserve some properties of the sphere-like body at the expense of other properties.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The study of map projections is primarily about the characterization of their distortions.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] There is no limit to the number of possible map projections.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] More generally, projections are considered in several fields of pure mathematics, including differential geometry, projective geometry, and manifolds.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] However, the term *map projection* refers specifically to a cartographic projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Despite the name's literal meaning, projection is not limited to perspective projections, such as those resulting from casting a shadow on a screen, or the rectilinear image produced by a pinhole camera on a flat film plate.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Rather, any mathematical function that transforms coordinates from the curved surface distinctly and smoothly to the plane is a projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Few projections in practical use are perspective.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Most of this article assumes that the surface to be mapped is that of a sphere.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The Earth and other large celestial bodies are generally better modeled as oblate spheroids, whereas small objects such as asteroids often have irregular shapes.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The surfaces of planetary bodies can be mapped even if they are too irregular to be modeled well with a sphere or ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The most well-known map projection is the Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] This map projection has the property of being conformal.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] However, it has been criticized throughout the 20th century for enlarging regions further from the equator.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] To contrast, equal-area projections such as the Sinusoidal projection and the Gall–Peters projection show the correct sizes of countries relative to each other, but distort angles.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The National Geographic Society and most atlases favor map projections that compromise between area and angular distortion, such as the Robinson projection and the Winkel tripel projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Map projections can be constructed to preserve some of these properties at the expense of others.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Because the Earth's curved surface is not isometric to a plane, preservation of shapes inevitably requires a variable scale and, consequently, non-proportional presentation of areas.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Similarly, an area-preserving projection can not be conformal, resulting in shapes and bearings distorted in most places of the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Each projection preserves, compromises, or approximates basic metric properties in different ways.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The purpose of the map determines which projection should form the base for the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Because maps have many different purposes, a diversity of projections have been created to suit those purposes.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Another consideration in the configuration of a projection is its compatibility with data sets to be used on the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Data sets are geographic information; their collection depends on the chosen datum (model) of the Earth.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Different datums assign slightly different coordinates to the same location, so in large scale maps, such as those from national mapping systems, it is important to match the datum to the projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The slight differences in coordinate assignation between different datums is not a concern for world maps or those of large regions, where such differences are reduced to imperceptibility.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Carl Friedrich Gauss's *Theorema Egregium* proved that a sphere's surface cannot be represented on a plane without distortion.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The same applies to other reference surfaces used as models for the Earth, such as oblate spheroids, ellipsoids, and geoids.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Since any map projection is a representation of one of those surfaces on a plane, all map projections distort.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The classical way of showing the distortion inherent in a projection is to use Tissot's indicatrix.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For a given point, using the scale factor *h* along the meridian, the scale factor *k* along the parallel, and the angle *θ*′ between them, Nicolas Tissot described how to construct an ellipse that illustrates the amount and orientation of the components of distortion.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] By spacing the ellipses regularly along the meridians and parallels, the network of indicatrices shows how distortion varies across the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Many other ways have been described of showing the distortion in projections.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Like Tissot's indicatrix, the **Goldberg-Gott indicatrix** is based on infinitesimals, and depicts *flexion* and *skewness* (bending and lopsidedness) distortions.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Rather than the original (enlarged) infinitesimal circle as in Tissot's indicatrix, some visual methods project finite shapes that span a part of the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For example, a small circle of fixed radius (e.g., 15 degrees angular radius).
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In the first half of the 20th century, projecting a human head onto different projections was common to show how distortion varies across one projection as compared to another.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In dynamic media, shapes of familiar coastlines and boundaries can be dragged across an interactive map to show how the projection distorts sizes and shapes according to position on the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Another way to visualize local distortion is through grayscale or color gradations whose shade represents the magnitude of the angular deformation or areal inflation.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Sometimes both are shown simultaneously by blending two colors to create a bivariate map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] To measure distortion globally across areas instead of at just a single point necessarily involves choosing priorities to reach a compromise.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Some schemes use distance distortion as a proxy for the combination of angular deformation and areal inflation; such methods arbitrarily choose what paths to measure and how to weight them in order to yield a single result.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Transformation of geographic coordinates (longitude and latitude) to Cartesian (*x*,*y*) or polar (*r*, *θ*) plane coordinates.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In large-scale maps, Cartesian coordinates normally have a simple relation to eastings and northings defined as a grid superimposed on the projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In small-scale maps, eastings and northings are not meaningful, and grids are not superimposed.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Some of the simplest map projections are literal projections, as obtained by placing a light source at some definite point relative to the globe and projecting its features onto a specified surface.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Although most projections are not defined in this way, picturing the light source-globe model can be helpful in understanding the basic concept of a map projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A surface that can be unfolded or unrolled into a plane or sheet without stretching, tearing or shrinking is called a *developable surface*.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The cylinder, cone and the plane are all developable surfaces.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The sphere and ellipsoid do not have developable surfaces, so any projection of them onto a plane will have to distort the image.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] One way of describing a projection is first to project from the Earth's surface to a developable surface such as a cylinder or cone, and then to unroll the surface into a plane.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] While the first step inevitably distorts some properties of the globe, the developable surface can then be unfolded without further distortion.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Once a choice is made between projecting onto a cylinder, cone, or plane, the **aspect** of the shape must be specified.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The aspect describes how the developable surface is placed relative to the globe: it may be *normal* (such that the surface's axis of symmetry coincides with the Earth's axis), *transverse* (at right angles to the Earth's axis) or *oblique* (any angle in between).
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The developable surface may also be either *tangent* or *secant* to the sphere or ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Tangent means the surface touches but does not slice through the globe; secant means the surface does slice through the globe.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Moving the developable surface away from contact with the globe never preserves or optimizes metric properties, so that possibility is not discussed further here.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Tangent and secant lines (*standard lines*) are represented undistorted.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] If these lines are a parallel of latitude, as in conical projections, it is called a *standard parallel*.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The *central meridian* is the meridian to which the globe is rotated before projecting.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The central meridian (usually written *λ*0) and a parallel of origin (usually written *φ*0) are often used to define the origin of the map projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A globe is the only way to represent the Earth with constant scale throughout the entire map in all directions.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A map cannot achieve that property for any area, no matter how small.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] It can, however, achieve constant scale along specific lines.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Projection construction is also affected by how the shape of the Earth or planetary body is approximated.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In the following section on projection categories, the earth is taken as a sphere in order to simplify the discussion.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] However, the Earth's actual shape is closer to an oblate ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Whether spherical or ellipsoidal, the principles discussed hold without loss of generality.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Selecting a model for a shape of the Earth involves choosing between the advantages and disadvantages of a sphere versus an ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Spherical models are useful for small-scale maps such as world atlases and globes, since the error at that scale is not usually noticeable or important enough to justify using the more complicated ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The ellipsoidal model is commonly used to construct topographic maps and for other large- and medium-scale maps that need to accurately depict the land surface.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Auxiliary latitudes are often employed in projecting the ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A third model is the geoid, a more complex and accurate representation of Earth's shape coincident with what mean sea level would be if there were no winds, tides, or land.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Compared to the best fitting ellipsoid, a geoidal model would change the characterization of important properties such as distance, conformality and equivalence.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Therefore, in geoidal projections that preserve such properties, the mapped graticule would deviate from a mapped ellipsoid's graticule.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Normally the geoid is not used as an Earth model for projections, however, because Earth's shape is very regular, with the undulation of the geoid amounting to less than 100 m from the ellipsoidal model out of the 6.3 million m Earth radius.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For irregular planetary bodies such as asteroids, however, sometimes models analogous to the geoid are used to project maps from.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Other regular solids are sometimes used as generalizations for smaller bodies' geoidal equivalent.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For example, Io is better modeled by triaxial ellipsoid or prolated spheroid with small eccentricities.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Haumea's shape is a Jacobi ellipsoid, with its major axis twice as long as its minor and with its middle axis one and half times as long as its minor.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] See map projection of the triaxial ellipsoid for further information.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] One way to classify map projections is based on the type of surface onto which the globe is projected.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The most common projection surfaces are cylindrical (e.g., Mercator), conic (e.g., Albers), and planar (e.g., stereographic).
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Many mathematical projections, however, do not neatly fit into any of these three projection methods.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Hence other peer categories have been described in the literature, such as pseudoconic, pseudocylindrical, pseudoazimuthal, retroazimuthal, and polyconic.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Another way to classify projections is according to properties of the model they preserve.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Because the sphere is not a developable surface, it is impossible to construct a map projection that is both equal-area and conformal.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The three developable surfaces (plane, cylinder, cone) provide useful models for understanding, describing, and developing map projections.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] However, these models are limited in two fundamental ways.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For one thing, most world projections in use do not fall into any of those categories.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For another thing, even most projections that do fall into those categories are not naturally attainable through physical projection.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Lee's objection refers to the way the terms *cylindrical*, *conic*, and *planar* (azimuthal) have been abstracted in the field of map projections.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] If maps were projected as in light shining through a globe onto a developable surface, then the spacing of parallels would follow a very limited set of possibilities.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Has parallels constrained to where they fall when light shines through the globe onto the cylinder, with the light source someplace along the line formed by the intersection of the prime meridian with the equator, and the center of the sphere.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] (If you rotate the globe before projecting then the parallels and meridians will not necessarily still be straight lines.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Where the light source emanates along the line described in this last constraint is what yields the differences between the various "natural" cylindrical projections.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] But the term *cylindrical* as used in the field of map projections relaxes the last constraint entirely.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Instead the parallels can be placed according to any algorithm the designer has decided suits the needs of the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The famous Mercator projection is one in which the placement of parallels does not arise by projection; instead parallels are placed how they need to be in order to satisfy the property that a course of constant bearing is always plotted as a straight line.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A normal cylindrical projection is any projection in which meridians are mapped to equally spaced vertical lines and circles of latitude (parallels) are mapped to horizontal lines.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The mapping of meridians to vertical lines can be visualized by imagining a cylinder whose axis coincides with the Earth's axis of rotation.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] This cylinder is wrapped around the Earth, projected onto, and then unrolled.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] By the geometry of their construction, cylindrical projections stretch distances east-west.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The amount of stretch is the same at any chosen latitude on all cylindrical projections, and is given by the secant of the latitude as a multiple of the equator's scale.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In the first case (Mercator), the east-west scale always equals the north-south scale.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In the second case (central cylindrical), the north-south scale exceeds the east-west scale everywhere away from the equator.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Each remaining case has a pair of secant lines—a pair of identical latitudes of opposite sign (or else the equator) at which the east-west scale matches the north-south-scale.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Normal cylindrical projections map the whole Earth as a finite rectangle, except in the first two cases, where the rectangle stretches infinitely tall while retaining constant width.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A transverse cylindrical projection is a cylindrical projection that in the tangent case uses a great circle along a meridian as contact line for the cylinder.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] An oblique cylindrical projection aligns with a great circle, but not the equator and not a meridian.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Pseudocylindrical projections represent the *central* meridian as a straight line segment.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Other meridians are longer than the central meridian and bow outward, away from the central meridian.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Pseudocylindrical projections map parallels as straight lines.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Along parallels, each point from the surface is mapped at a distance from the central meridian that is proportional to its difference in longitude from the central meridian.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Therefore, meridians are equally spaced along a given parallel.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] On a pseudocylindrical map, any point further from the equator than some other point has a higher latitude than the other point, preserving north-south relationships.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] This trait is useful when illustrating phenomena that depend on latitude, such as climate.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The HEALPix projection combines an equal-area cylindrical projection in equatorial regions with the Collignon projection in polar areas.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The term *conic projection* is used to refer to any projection in which meridians are mapped to equally spaced lines radiating out from the apex and circles of latitude (parallels) are mapped to circular arcs centered on the apex.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] When making a conic map, the map maker arbitrarily picks two standard parallels.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Those standard parallels may be visualized as secant lines where the cone intersects the globe—or, if the map maker chooses the same parallel twice, as the tangent line where the cone is tangent to the globe.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The resulting conic map has low distortion in scale, shape, and area near those standard parallels.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Distances along the parallels to the north of both standard parallels or to the south of both standard parallels are stretched; distances along parallels between the standard parallels are compressed.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] When a single standard parallel is used, distances along all other parallels are stretched.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Azimuthal projections have the property that directions from a central point are preserved and therefore great circles through the central point are represented by straight lines on the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The mapping of radial lines can be visualized by imagining a plane tangent to the Earth, with the central point as tangent point.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The radial scale is *r′*(*d*) and the transverse scale *r*(*d*)/(*R* sin ⁠*d*/*R*⁠) where *R* is the radius of the Earth.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Polyhedral map projections use a polyhedron to subdivide the globe into faces, and then projects each face to the globe.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The most well-known polyhedral map projection is Buckminster Fuller's Dymaxion map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Conformal, or orthomorphic, map projections preserve angles locally, implying that they map infinitesimal circles of constant size anywhere on the Earth to infinitesimal circles of varying sizes on the map.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In contrast, mappings that are not conformal distort most such small circles into ellipses of distortion.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] An important consequence of conformality is that relative angles at each point of the map are correct, and the local scale (although varying throughout the map) in every direction around any one point is constant.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Equal-area maps preserve area measure, generally distorting shapes in order to do so.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Equal-area maps are also called *equivalent* or *authalic*.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] If the length of the line segment connecting two projected points on the plane is proportional to the geodesic distance between the two unprojected points on the globe, then we say that distance has been preserved between those two points.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] An **equidistant projection** preserves distances from one or two special points to all other points.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The special point or points may get stretched into a line or curve segment when projected.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In that case, the point on the line or curve segment closest to the point being measured to must be used to measure the distance.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Compromise projections give up the idea of perfectly preserving metric properties, seeking instead to strike a balance between distortions, or to simply make things look right.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Most of these types of projections distort shape in the polar regions more than at the equator.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The mathematics of projection do not permit any particular map projection to be best for everything.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Thus, many projections exist to serve the many uses of maps and their vast range of scales.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Modern national mapping systems typically employ a transverse Mercator or close variant for large-scale maps in order to preserve conformality and low variation in scale over small areas.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] For smaller-scale maps, such as those spanning continents or the entire world, many projections are in common use according to their fitness for the purpose, such as Winkel tripel, Robinson and Mollweide.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Reference maps of the world often appear on compromise projections.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Due to distortions inherent in any map of the world, the choice of projection becomes largely one of aesthetics.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] Thematic maps normally require an equal area projection so that phenomena per unit area are shown in correct proportion.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] However, representing area ratios correctly necessarily distorts shapes more than many maps that are not equal-area.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] The Mercator projection, developed for navigational purposes, has often been used in world maps where other projections would have been more appropriate.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] This problem has long been recognized even outside professional circles.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] A controversy in the 1980s over the Peters map motivated the American Cartographic Association (now the Cartography and Geographic Information Society) to produce a series of booklets (including *Which Map Is Best*) designed to educate the public about map projections and distortion in maps.
[src:map-projections/map-projection] In 1989 and 1990, after some internal debate, seven North American geographic organizations adopted a resolution recommending against using any rectangular projection (including Mercator and Gall–Peters) for reference maps of the world.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The **Mercator projection** (/mərˈkeɪtər/) is a conformal cylindrical map projection first presented by Flemish geographer and mapmaker Gerardus Mercator in 1569.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In the 18th century, it became the standard map projection for navigation due to its property of representing rhumb lines as straight lines.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] When applied to world maps, the Mercator projection inflates the size of lands the farther they are from the equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Therefore, landmasses such as Greenland and Antarctica appear far larger than they actually are relative to landmasses near the equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Its use for maps other than marine charts declined throughout the 20th century, but resurged in the 21st century due to characteristics favorable for World-Wide-Web maps.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] German polymath Erhard Etzlaub engraved miniature "compass maps" (about 10×8 cm) of Europe and parts of Africa that spanned latitudes 0°–67° to allow adjustment of his portable pocket-size sundials.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The projection found on these maps, dating to 1511, was stated by John Snyder in 1987 to be the same projection as Mercator's.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, given the geometry of a sundial, these maps may well have been based on the similar central cylindrical projection, a limiting case of the gnomonic projection, which is the basis for a sundial.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Snyder amended his assessment to "a similar projection" in 1993.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Portuguese mathematician and cosmographer Pedro Nunes first described the mathematical principle of the rhumb line or loxodrome, a path with constant bearing as measured relative to true north, which can be used in marine navigation to pick which compass bearing to follow.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In 1537, he proposed constructing a nautical atlas composed of several large-scale sheets in the equirectangular projection as a way to minimize distortion of directions.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] If these sheets were brought to the same scale and assembled, they would approximate the Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In 1541, Flemish geographer and mapmaker Gerardus Mercator included a network of rhumb lines on a terrestrial globe he made for Nicolas Perrenot.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In 1569, Mercator announced a new projection by publishing a large world map measuring 202 by 124 cm (80 by 49 in) and printed in eighteen separate sheets.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Mercator titled the map *Nova et Aucta Orbis Terrae Descriptio ad Usum Navigantium Emendata*: "A new and augmented description of Earth corrected for the use of sailors".
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This title, along with an elaborate explanation for using the projection that appears as a section of text on the map, shows that Mercator understood exactly what he had achieved and that he intended the projection to aid navigation.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Mercator never explained the method of construction or how he arrived at it.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Various hypotheses have been tendered over the years, but in any case Mercator's friendship with Pedro Nunes and his access to the loxodromic tables Nunes created likely aided his efforts.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] English mathematician Edward Wright published the first accurate tables for constructing the projection in 1599 and, in more detail, in 1610, calling his treatise "Certaine Errors in Navigation".
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The first mathematical formulation was publicized around 1645 by a mathematician named Henry Bond (c.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, the mathematics involved were developed but never published by mathematician Thomas Harriot starting around 1589.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The development of the Mercator projection represented a major breakthrough in the nautical cartography of the 16th century.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, it was much ahead of its time, since the old navigational and surveying techniques were not compatible with its use in navigation.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Two main problems prevented its immediate application: the impossibility of determining the longitude at sea with adequate accuracy and the fact that magnetic directions, instead of geographical directions, were used in navigation.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Only in the middle of the 18th century, after the marine chronometer was invented and the spatial distribution of magnetic declination was known, could the Mercator projection be fully adopted by navigators.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Despite those position-finding limitations, the Mercator projection can be found in many world maps in the centuries following Mercator's first publication.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, it did not begin to dominate world maps until the 19th century, when the problem of position determination had been largely solved.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Once the Mercator became the usual projection for commercial and educational maps, it came under persistent criticism from cartographers for its unbalanced representation of landmasses and its inability to usefully show the polar regions.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The criticisms leveled against inappropriate use of the Mercator projection resulted in a flurry of new inventions in the late 19th and early 20th century, often directly touted as alternatives to the Mercator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Due to these pressures, publishers gradually reduced their use of the projection over the course of the 20th century.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, the advent of Web mapping gave the projection an abrupt resurgence in the form of the Web Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Today, the Mercator can be found in marine charts, occasional world maps, and Web mapping services, but commercial atlases have largely abandoned it, and wall maps of the world can be found in many alternative projections.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Google Maps, which relied on it since 2005, still uses it for local-area maps but dropped the projection from desktop platforms in 2017 for maps that are zoomed out of local areas.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Many other online mapping services still exclusively use the Web Mercator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Afterward, this cylinder is unrolled onto a flat plane to make a map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In this interpretation, the scale of the surface is preserved exactly along the circle where the cylinder touches the sphere, but increases nonlinearly for points further from the contact circle.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This is sometimes visualized as a projection onto a cylinder which is *secant* to (cuts) the sphere, though this picture is misleading insofar as the standard parallels are not spaced the same distance apart on the map as the shortest distance between them through the interior of the sphere.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The original and most common aspect of the Mercator projection for maps of Earth is the normal aspect, for which the axis of the cylinder is Earth's axis of rotation which passes through the North and South poles, and the contact circle is Earth's equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] As for all cylindrical projections in normal aspect, circles of latitude and meridians of longitude are straight and perpendicular to each other on the map, forming a grid of rectangles.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] While circles of latitude on Earth are smaller the closer they are to the poles, they are stretched in an East–West direction to have uniform length on any cylindrical map projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Among cylindrical projections, the Mercator projection is the unique projection which balances this East–West stretching by a precisely corresponding North–South stretching, so that at every location the scale is locally uniform and angles are preserved.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Because the linear scale of a Mercator map in normal aspect increases with latitude, it distorts the size of geographical objects far from the equator and conveys a distorted perception of the overall geometry of the planet.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] At latitudes greater than 70° north or south, the Mercator projection is practically unusable, because the linear scale becomes infinitely large at the poles.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] A Mercator map can therefore never fully show the polar areas (but see Uses below for applications of the oblique and transverse Mercator projections).
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection is often compared to and confused with the central cylindrical projection, which is the result of projecting points from the sphere onto a tangent cylinder along straight radial lines, as if from a light source placed at Earth's center.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Both have extreme distortion far from the equator and cannot show the poles.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, they are different projections and have different properties.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] As with all map projections, the shapes or sizes are distortions of the true layout of Earth's surface.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection exaggerates areas far from the equator; the closer to Earth's poles, the greater the distortion.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Because of great land area distortions, critics like George Kellaway and Irving Fisher consider the projection unsuitable for general world maps.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] It has been conjectured to have influenced people's views of the world: because it shows countries near the Equator as too small when compared to those of Europe and North America, it has been supposed to cause people to consider those countries as less important.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The areal exaggerations of the Mercator projection were suspected to have fuelled Donald Trump's attempt to annex Greenland in 2025, particularly in light of Trump's previous exclamation that "I love maps.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] And I always said, 'Look at the size of this.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Mercator himself used the equal-area sinusoidal projection to show relative areas.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] However, despite such criticisms, the Mercator projection was, especially in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, perhaps the most common projection used in world maps.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Atlases largely stopped using the Mercator projection for world maps or for areas distant from the equator in the 1940s, preferring other cylindrical projections, or forms of equal-area projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection is, however, still commonly used for areas near the equator where distortion is minimal.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] It is also frequently found in maps of time zones.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Arno Peters stirred controversy beginning in 1972 when he proposed what is now usually called the Gall–Peters projection to remedy the problems of the Mercator, claiming it to be his own original work without referencing prior work by cartographers such as Gall's work from 1855.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The projection he promoted is a specific parameterization of the cylindrical equal-area projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In response, a 1989 resolution by seven North American geographical groups disparaged using cylindrical projections for general-purpose world maps, which would include both the Mercator and the Gall–Peters.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] As of 2025 the African Union supports a campaign favoring the Equal Earth projection over the Mercator projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Practically every marine chart in print is based on the Mercator projection due to its uniquely favorable properties for navigation.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] It is also commonly used by street map services hosted on the Internet, due to its uniquely favorable properties for local-area maps computed on demand.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Mercator projections were also important in the mathematical development of plate tectonics in the 1960s.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The Mercator projection was designed for use in marine navigation because of its unique property of representing any course of constant bearing as a straight segment.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Such a course, known as a rhumb (alternately called a rhumb line or loxodrome) is preferred in marine navigation because ships can sail in a constant compass direction.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This reduces the difficult, error-prone course corrections that otherwise would be necessary when sailing a different course.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For small distances (compared to the radius of Earth), the difference between the rhumb and the great circle course is negligible.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Even for longer distances, the simplicity of the constant bearing makes it attractive.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] As observed by Mercator, on such a course the ship would not arrive by the shortest route but it will surely arrive.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Sailing a rhumb meant that all that the sailors had to do was keep a constant course as long as they knew where they were when they started, where they intended to be when they finished, and had a map in Mercator projection that correctly showed those two coordinates.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Many major online street mapping services (Bing Maps, Google Maps, Mapbox, MapQuest, OpenStreetMap, Yahoo!
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Maps, and others) use a variant of the Mercator projection for their map images called Web Mercator or Google Web Mercator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Despite its obvious scale variation at the world level (small scales), the projection is well-suited as an interactive world map that can be zoomed seamlessly to local (large-scale) maps, where there is relatively little distortion due to the variant projection's near-conformality.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The major online street mapping services' tiling systems display most of the world at the lowest zoom level as a single square image, excluding the polar regions by truncation at latitudes of *φ*max = ±85.05113°.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] (See below.) Latitude values outside this range are mapped using a different relationship that does not diverge at *φ* = ±90°.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] A transverse Mercator projection tilts the cylinder axis so that it is perpendicular to Earth's axis.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The tangent standard line then coincides with a meridian and its opposite meridian, giving a constant scale factor along those meridians, and a near-constant one within a band of a few degrees of longitude around them.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This property makes such a projection useful for mapping regions that are either compact or predominately north–south in extent.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In its more complex ellipsoidal form, most national grid systems around the world use the transverse Mercator, as does the Universal Transverse Mercator coordinate system.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] An oblique Mercator projection tilts the cylinder axis away from Earth's axis to an angle of one's choosing, so that its tangent or secant lines of contact are circles that are also tilted relative to Earth's parallels of latitude.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Practical uses for the oblique projection, such as national grid systems, use ellipsoidal developments of the oblique Mercator in order to keep scale variation low along the surface projection of the cylinder's axis.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The animation below shows a continuous transformation between the normal Mercator projection and the transverse projection, running through the intermediate oblique states.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] A rhumb line (blue) and great circle (red) from Tokyo, Japan, to Callao, Peru, change according to the projection's aspect.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The rhumb between them is straight only on the normal projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] On one of the intermediate oblique projections, the great-circle path between the two cities is straight.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In this plot the y-axis is always the projected axis of the cylinder.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The sphere is rotated inside the cylinder to change aspect.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Initially the axis is normal to the equator (projected as the thick green line) but ends transverse to it, when the projected equator extends to infinity in the vertical direction.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] where ⁠ R ⁠ is an arbitrary scale factor which determines the size of the resulting map, ln is the natural logarithm, and tan is the trigonometric tangent function.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Although the surface of Earth is better modelled by an oblate ellipsoid of revolution, for small scale maps the ellipsoid is approximated by a sphere of radius *a*, where *a* is approximately 6,371 km.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This spherical approximation of Earth can be modelled by a smaller sphere of radius *R*, called the *globe* in this section.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The globe determines the scale of the map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The various cylindrical projections specify how the geographic detail is transferred from the globe to a cylinder tangential to it at the equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The cylinder is then unrolled to give the planar map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The fraction ⁠*R*/*a*⁠ is called the representative fraction (RF) or the principal scale of the projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] A cylindrical map projection is specified by formulae linking the geographic coordinates of latitude *φ* and longitude *λ* to Cartesian coordinates on the map with origin on the equator and *x*-axis along the equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] By construction, all points on the same meridian lie on the same *generator* of the cylinder at a constant value of *x*, but the distance *y* along the generator (measured from the equator) is an arbitrary function of latitude, *y*(*φ*).
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In general this function does not describe the geometrical projection (as of light rays onto a screen) from the centre of the globe to the cylinder, which is only one of an unlimited number of ways to conceptually project a cylindrical map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Since the cylinder is tangential to the globe at the equator, the scale factor between globe and cylinder is unity on the equator but nowhere else.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In particular since the radius of a parallel, or circle of latitude, is *R* cos *φ*, the corresponding parallel on the map must have been stretched by a factor of ⁠1/cos *φ*⁠ = sec *φ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This scale factor on the parallel is conventionally denoted by *k* and the corresponding scale factor on the meridian is denoted by *h*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] One implication of that is the "isotropy of scale factors", which means that the point scale factor is independent of direction, so that small shapes are preserved by the projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This implies that the vertical scale factor, *h*, equals the horizontal scale factor, *k*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The graph shows the variation of this scale factor with latitude.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The area scale factor is the product of the parallel and meridian scales *hk* = sec2*φ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For Greenland, taking 73° as a median latitude, *hk* = 11.7.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For Australia, taking 25° as a median latitude, *hk* = 1.2.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For Great Britain, taking 55° as a median latitude, *hk* = 3.04.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The variation with latitude is sometimes indicated by multiple bar scales as shown below.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The classic way of showing the distortion inherent in a projection is to use Tissot's indicatrix.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Nicolas Tissot noted that the scale factors at a point on a map projection, specified by the numbers *h* and *k*, define an ellipse at that point.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For cylindrical projections, the axes of the ellipse are aligned to the meridians and parallels.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For the Mercator projection, *h* = *k*, so the ellipses degenerate into circles with radius proportional to the value of the scale factor for that latitude.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] These circles are rendered on the projected map with extreme variation in size, indicative of Mercator's scale variations.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] As discussed above, the isotropy condition implies that ⁠ $h=k=\sec \varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Consider a point on the globe of radius ⁠ R ⁠ with longitude ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ and latitude ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠, expressed in radians.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] If ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ is increased by an infinitesimal amount ⁠ $d\varphi$ ⁠, the point moves ⁠ $R\,d\varphi$ ⁠ along a meridian of the globe of radius ⁠ R ⁠, so the corresponding change in ⁠ y ⁠ is ⁠ $dy=hR\,d\varphi =R\sec \varphi \,d\varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Therefore ⁠ $y'(\varphi )=R\sec \varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Similarly, increasing ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ by ⁠ $d\lambda$ ⁠ moves the point ⁠ $R\cos \varphi \,d\lambda$ ⁠ along a parallel of the globe, so ⁠ $dx=kR\cos \varphi \,d\lambda =Rd\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The value ⁠ $\lambda _{0}$ ⁠ is the longitude of an arbitrary central meridian, often the prime meridian ⁠ $\lambda _{0}=0$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The vertical coordinate ⁠ y ⁠ was historically called the *meridional part* of ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In the figure, ⁠ y ⁠ is plotted against ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ for the case ⁠ $R=1$ ⁠, such that it equals the anti-gudermannian of ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠; it tends to infinity at the poles.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The numerical value of ⁠ y ⁠ is not usually shown on printed maps; some maps show a non-linear scale of latitudes, but more often than not maps show only a graticule of selected meridians and parallels.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] As a conformal map, the Mercator projection can be conveniently expressed using a single complex number to represent each point on the sphere rather than a pair of real-number coordinates.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The complex number representing each point on this so-called Riemann sphere is found by conformally mapping the sphere onto the complex plane via the stereographic projection.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] From there, the Mercator projection is just the complex logarithm, ⁠ $z\mapsto \log z$ ⁠, a conformal map of the complex plane (with the exception of the origin, whose logarithm is undefined) onto a two-infinite-ended cylinder.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Starting from geographic coordinates ⁠ $(\lambda ,\varphi )$ ⁠ in radians, the stereographic projection yields a complex number ⁠ $\textstyle z=e^{\lambda i}\tan {\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{4}}\pi -{\tfrac {1}{2}}\varphi {\bigr )}$ ⁠, with the North Pole mapped to the origin.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The imaginary part of the resulting complex number represents the longitude and its real part represents the negative projected latitude.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] To better match prevailing conventions about the plotting of complex numbers and world maps it can be rotated a quarter turn and scaled arbitrarily by multiplying by a scaling factor ⁠ $-Ri$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Finding the longitude as an inverse of the ⁠ x ⁠ coordinate is trivial.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The latitude can be found as an inverse of ⁠ y ⁠ as the gudermannian of ⁠ $y/R$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] There are many identities relating the circular angle ⁠ $\varphi$ ⁠ to its anti-gudermannian ⁠ $\operatorname {gd} ^{-1}\varphi =y/R$ ⁠, a hyperbolic angle, which can be used to construct alternate expressions for the functions from one to the other.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] where sinh is the hyperbolic sine function.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] where tanh is the hyperbolic tangent function.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The above formulae are written in terms of the globe radius ⁠ R ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] It is often convenient to work directly with the map width ⁠ W ⁠, in terms of which, assuming the map shows the whole globe, ⁠ $R=W/2\pi$ ⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The ordinate *y* of the Mercator projection becomes infinite at the poles and the map must be truncated at some latitude less than ninety degrees.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Mercator's original map is truncated at 80°N and 66°S with the result that European countries were moved toward the centre of the map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Even more extreme truncations have been used: a Finnish school atlas was truncated at approximately 76°N and 56°S, an aspect ratio of 1.97.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Much Web-based mapping uses a zoomable version of the Mercator projection with an aspect ratio of one.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In this case the maximum latitude attained must correspond to *y* = ±⁠*W*/2⁠, or equivalently ⁠*y*/*R*⁠ = π.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The relations between *y*(*φ*) and properties of the projection, such as the transformation of angles and the variation in scale, follow from the geometry of corresponding *small* elements on the globe and map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The figure below shows a point P at latitude *φ* and longitude *λ* on the globe and a nearby point Q at latitude *φ* + *δφ* and longitude *λ* + *δλ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The vertical lines PK and MQ are arcs of meridians of length *Rδφ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The horizontal lines PM and KQ are arcs of parallels of length *R*(cos *φ*)*δλ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The corresponding points on the projection define a rectangle of width *δx* and height *δy*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Since the meridians are mapped to lines of constant *x*, we must have *x* = *R*(*λ* − *λ*0) and *δx* = *Rδλ*, (*λ* in radians).
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] In the case of the Mercator projection, *y'*(*φ*) = *R* sec *φ*, so this gives us *h* = *k* and *α* = *β*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The fact that *h* = *k* is the isotropy of scale factors discussed above.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The fact that *α* = *β* reflects another implication of the mapping being conformal, namely the fact that a sailing course of constant azimuth on the globe is mapped into the same constant grid bearing on the map.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Converting ruler distance on the Mercator map into true (great circle) distance on the sphere is straightforward along the equator, but not at other latitudes.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] One problem is the variation of scale with latitude.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Another problem is that straight lines on the map (rhumb lines), other than the meridians or the equator, do not correspond to great circles.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The distinction between rhumb (sailing) distance and great circle (true) distance was understood by Mercator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] (See Legend 12 on the 1569 map.) He asserted that the rhumb line distance is an acceptable approximation for true great circle distance for courses of short or moderate distance, particularly at lower latitudes.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] He quantified his statement: "When the great circle distances which are to be measured in the vicinity of the equator do not exceed 20 degrees of a great circle, or 15 degrees near Spain and France, or 8 and even 10 degrees in northern parts it is convenient to use rhumb line distances".
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] With radius and great circle circumference equal to 6,371 km and 40,030 km respectively an RF of ⁠1/300M⁠, for which *R* = 2.12 cm and *W* = 13.34 cm, implies that a ruler measurement of 3 mm. in any direction from a point on the equator corresponds to approximately 900 km.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The corresponding distances for latitudes 20°, 40°, 60° and 80° are 846 km, 689 km, 450 km and 156 km respectively.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Longer distances require various approaches.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Scale is unity on the equator (for a non-secant projection).
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For the above model, with RF = ⁠1/300M⁠, 1 cm corresponds to 3,000 km.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For the above model 1 cm corresponds to 1,500 km at a latitude of 60°.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This is not the shortest distance between the chosen endpoints on the parallel because a parallel is not a great circle.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The difference is small for short distances but increases as *λ*, the longitudinal separation, increases.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For two points, A and B, separated by 10° of longitude on the parallel at 60° the distance along the parallel is approximately 0.5 km greater than the great circle distance.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] (The distance AB along the parallel is (*a* cos *φ*) *λ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The length of the chord AB is 2(*a* cos *φ*) sin ⁠*λ*/2⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] On the other hand, the geodesic between these points is a great circle arc through the pole subtending an angle of 60° at the center: the length of this arc is one sixth of the great circle circumference, about 6,672 km.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The difference is 3,338 km so the ruler distance measured from the map is quite misleading even after correcting for the latitude variation of the scale factor.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] A meridian of the map is a great circle on the globe but the continuous scale variation means ruler measurement alone cannot yield the true distance between distant points on the meridian.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] If the latitudes of the end points cannot be determined with confidence then they can be found instead by calculation on the ruler distance.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] where *R* may be calculated from the width *W* of the map by *R* = ⁠*W*/2π⁠.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For example, on a map with *R* = 1 the values of *y* = 0, 1, 2, 3 correspond to latitudes of *φ* = 0°, 50°, 75°, 84° and therefore the successive intervals of 1 cm on the map correspond to latitude intervals on the globe of 50°, 25°, 9° and distances of 5,560 km, 2,780 km, and 1,000 km on Earth.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] A straight line on the Mercator map at angle *α* to the meridians is a rhumb line.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] When *α* = ⁠π/2⁠ or ⁠3π/2⁠ the rhumb corresponds to one of the parallels; only one, the equator, is a great circle.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] When *α* = 0 or π it corresponds to a meridian great circle (if continued around the globe).
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] For all other values it is a spiral from pole to pole on the globe intersecting all meridians at the same angle, and is thus not a great circle.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This section discusses only the last of these cases.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] If *α* is neither 0 nor π then the above figure of the infinitesimal elements shows that the length of an infinitesimal rhumb line on the sphere between latitudes *φ*; and *φ* + *δφ* is *a* sec *α* *δφ*.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Once again, if Δ*φ* may be read directly from an accurate latitude scale on the map, then the rhumb distance between map points with latitudes *φ*1 and *φ*2 is given by the above.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] These formulae give rhumb distances on the sphere which may differ greatly from true distances whose determination requires more sophisticated calculations.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] When Earth is modelled by a spheroid (ellipsoid of revolution) the Mercator projection must be modified if it is to remain conformal.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The scale factor *k* is unity on the equator, as it must be since the cylinder is tangential to the ellipsoid at the equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The ellipsoidal correction of the scale factor increases with latitude but it is never greater than *e*2, a correction of less than 1%.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The value of *e*2 is about 0.006 for all reference ellipsoids.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] This is much smaller than the scale inaccuracy, except very close to the equator.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] Only accurate Mercator projections of regions near the equator will necessitate the ellipsoidal corrections.
[src:map-projections/mercator-projection] The inverse is solved iteratively, as the isometric latitude is involved.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The **Universal Transverse Mercator** (**UTM**) is a projected coordinate system based on the *transverse Mercator* map projection of the Earth spheroid.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] As a map projection, it transforms geographic coordinates of locations on Earth's surface to assign plane coordinates to them.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] It is a horizontal position representation, which means it ignores altitude and treats the earth surface as an oblate ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The system divides Earth into 60 zones and projects each to the plane as a basis for its coordinates.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Specifying a location means specifying the zone and the *x*, *y* coordinate in that plane.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] UTM parameter specifications vary by nation or region or mapping system.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] However, most zones in UTM span 6 degrees of longitude, and each has a designated central meridian.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] In each zone, the scale factor at the central meridian is specified to be 0.9996 of true scale (for most UTM systems in use).
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Therefore maps, atlases, and topographic grid systems built from an appropriate collection of UTM zones cover a region with planar maps with well-controlled, minimal distortion.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] For this reason, UTM coordinates are used in many nations and regions for topographic mapping, as well as more generally for pinpointing locations.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) website states that the system was developed by the United States Army Corps of Engineers, starting in the early 1940s.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] It was probably carried out by the Abteilung für Luftbildwesen (Department for Aerial Photography).
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] From 1947 onward the US Army employed a very similar system, but with the now-standard 0.9996 scale factor at the central meridian as opposed to the German 1.0.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] For areas within the contiguous United States the Clarke Ellipsoid of 1866 was used.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] For the remaining areas of Earth, including Hawaii, the International Ellipsoid was used.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] While historically UTM has been used with a range of geodetic datums, since the proliferation of civilian GPS usage, the World Geodetic System WGS84 ellipsoid has become the default for specifying a point's longitude and latitude.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The WGS84 datum has therefore become the implicit default for UTM coordinates as well, if no alternate datum is specified.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] In North America, WGS84 UTM coordinates of a given point can differ up to 200 meters from older ones based on NAD27, for instance.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Prior to the development of the Universal Transverse Mercator coordinate system, several European nations demonstrated the utility of grid-based conformal maps by mapping their territory during the interwar period.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Calculating the distance between two points on these maps could be performed more easily in the field (using the Pythagorean theorem) than was possible using the trigonometric formulas required under the graticule-based system of latitude and longitude.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] In the post-war years, these concepts were extended into the Universal Transverse Mercator/Universal Polar Stereographic (UTM/UPS) coordinate system, which is a global (or universal) system of grid-based maps.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The transverse Mercator projection is a variant of the Mercator projection, which was originally developed by the Flemish geographer and cartographer Gerardus Mercator, in 1570.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] This projection is conformal, which means it preserves angles and therefore shapes across small regions.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The UTM system divides the Earth into 60 zones, each 6° of longitude in width.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Zone 1 covers longitude 180° to 174° W; zone numbering increases eastward to zone 60, which covers longitude 174°E to 180°.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The polar regions south of 80°S and north of 84°N are excluded, and instead covered by the universal polar stereographic (UPS) coordinate system.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Each of the 60 zones uses a transverse Mercator projection that can map a region of large north-south extent with low distortion.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] By using narrow zones of 6° of longitude (up to 668 km) in width, and reducing the scale factor along the central meridian to 0.9996 (a reduction of 1:2500), the amount of distortion is held below 1 part in 1,000 inside each zone.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Distortion of scale increases to 1.0010 at the zone boundaries along the equator.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] In each zone the scale factor of the central meridian reduces the diameter of the transverse cylinder to produce a secant projection with two standard lines, or lines of true scale, about 180 km on each side of, and about parallel to, the central meridian (Arc cos 0.9996 = 1.62° at the Equator).
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The scale is less than 1 inside the standard lines and greater than 1 outside them, but the overall distortion is minimized.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The UTM zones are uniform across the globe, except in two areas.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] On the southwest coast of Norway, zone 32 is extended 3° further west, and zone 31 is correspondingly shrunk to cover only open water.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Also, in the region around Svalbard, the zones 32, 34 and 36 are not used, while zones 31 (9° wide), 33 (12° wide), 35 (12° wide), and 37 (9° wide) are extended to cover the gaps.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Distortion of scale increases in each UTM zone as the boundaries between the UTM zones are approached.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] However, it is often convenient or necessary to measure a series of locations on a single grid when some are located in two adjacent zones.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Around the boundaries of large scale maps (1:100,000 or larger) coordinates for both adjoining UTM zones are usually printed within a minimum distance of 40 km on either side of a zone boundary.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Ideally, the coordinates of each position should be measured on the grid for the zone in which they are located, but because the scale factor is still relatively small near zone boundaries, it is possible to overlap measurements into an adjoining zone for some distance when necessary.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Latitude bands are not a part of UTM, but rather a part of the military grid reference system (MGRS).
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] They are however sometimes included in UTM notation.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Including latitude bands in UTM notation can lead to ambiguous coordinates—as the letter "S" either refers to the southern hemisphere or a latitude band in the northern hemisphere—and should therefore be avoided.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] A position on the Earth is given by the UTM zone number and hemisphere designator and the easting and northing planar coordinate pair in that zone.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The point of origin of each UTM zone is the intersection of the equator and the zone's central meridian.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] To avoid dealing with negative numbers, a false Easting of −500000 meters is added to the central meridian.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Thus a point that has an easting of 400000 meters is about 100 km west of the central meridian.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] For most such points, the true distance would be slightly more than 100 km as measured on the surface of the Earth because of the distortion of the projection.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] UTM eastings range from about 166000 meters to 834000 meters at the equator.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] In the Northern Hemisphere positions are measured northward from zero at the equator.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The maximum "northing" value is about 9300000 meters at latitude 84 degrees North, the north end of the UTM zones.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The Southern Hemisphere's northing at the equator is set at 10000000 meters.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Northings decrease southward from these 10000000 meters to about 1100000 meters at 80 degrees South, the south end of the UTM zones.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Therefore, no point has a negative northing value.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Two points in Zone 17 have these coordinates, one in the Northern Hemisphere and one in the south; the non-ambiguous format is to specify the full zone and hemisphere designator, that is, "17N 630084 4833438".
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] These formulae are truncated version of Transverse Mercator: flattening series, which were originally derived by Johann Heinrich Louis Krüger in 1912.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] They are accurate to around a millimeter within 3000 km of the central meridian.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Concise commentaries for their derivation have also been given.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The WGS 84 spatial reference system describes Earth as an oblate spheroid along north-south axis with an equatorial radius of $a=6378.137$ km and an inverse flattening of $1/f=298.257\,223\,563$ .
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Taking a point of latitude $\,\varphi$ and of longitude $\,\lambda$ and computing its UTM coordinates as well as point scale factor $k\,\!$ and meridian convergence $\gamma \,\!$ using a reference meridian of longitude $\lambda _{0}$ .
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] By convention, in the Northern Hemisphere $N_{0}=0$ km and in the Southern Hemisphere $N_{0}=10000$ km.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] In the following formulas, the distances are in kilometers and angles are in radians.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] where E is Easting, N is Northing, k is the Scale Factor, and $\gamma$ is the Grid Convergence.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Since transverse Mercator projections are conformal, maps in UTM coordinates do not distort subtended angles or local shapes, and scale distortion is isotropic.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Distortion at a specific point is wholly described by the (direction-free) scale factor k and grid convergence angle $\gamma$ , which both depend on the displacement from the central meridian $\lambda _{0}$ of the UTM zone used.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] More specifically, on a UTM map, meridians other than the central one are slightly curved, their rotation (tangent line at any point) given by the grid convergence angle $\gamma$ there.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The scale factor increases from $k_{0}$ at the central meridian.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The value of each depends on the latitude $\phi$ and the deviation in longitude $\Delta \lambda =\lambda -\lambda _{0}$ .
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] The quadratic dependence for scale factor makes it fairly constant around the central meridian, increasing more rapidly when closer to a zone's edge.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] At zone edges, $\Delta \lambda =\pm 3$ °, the scale factor is approximately 1.0010 at the equator and 1.0005 at latitude 45°.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] At a distance of about 180 km east or west of the central meridian, the scale factor is precisely 1, regardless of latitude.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] Alternative coordinate systems with narrower zones, such as MTM or certain U.S.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] SPCSes, allow for quadratically lower scale distortion at the expense of narrower single-zone coverage.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] These formulas for $\gamma$ and k are particularly relevant for converting paths described by ground distances and astronomic (true) bearings, for instance land surveyors' measurements, to UTM coordinates.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] For a small-scale survey (extent <1 km), $\gamma$ and k are both essentially constant for the whole area covered.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] However, for conversion of ground distance to grid, correcting the scale factor for elevation is also necessary (projecting down to the reference geoid at elevation zero).
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] For medium-scale surveys (a few km in east-west extent), the change in $\gamma$ over the area represented may be material, as shown by the part of the formula using E .
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] However, the variation of k over the area will be negligible.
[src:map-projections/universal-transverse-mercator-coordinate-system] These approximations are too inaccurate for larger scales, such as for infrastructure projects or longer administrative boundary retracements.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Web Mercator is a slight variant of the Mercator projection, one used primarily in Web-based mapping programs.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] It uses the same formulas as the standard Mercator as used for small-scale maps.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] However, the Web Mercator uses the spherical formulas at all scales whereas large-scale Mercator maps normally use the ellipsoidal form of the projection.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The discrepancy is imperceptible at the global scale but causes maps of local areas to deviate slightly from true ellipsoidal Mercator maps at the same scale.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] While the Web Mercator's formulas are for the spherical form of the Mercator, geographical coordinates are required to be in the WGS 84 ellipsoidal datum.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] This discrepancy causes the projection to be slightly non-conformal.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] General lack of understanding that the Web Mercator differs from standard Mercator usage has caused considerable confusion and misuse.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Mistaking Web Mercator for the standard Mercator during coordinate conversion can lead to deviations as much as 40 km on the ground.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] For all these reasons, the United States Department of Defense through the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency has declared this map projection to be unacceptable for any official use.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Unlike most map projections for the sphere, the Web Mercator uses the equatorial radius of the WGS 84 spheroid, rather than some compromise between the equatorial and polar radii.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] This results in a slightly larger map compared to the map's stated (nominal) scale than for most maps.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Because the Mercator projects the poles at infinity, a map using the Web Mercator projection cannot show the poles.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Services such as Google Maps cut off coverage at 85.051129° north and south.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] This is not a limitation for street maps, which is the primary purpose for such services.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The projection is neither strictly ellipsoidal nor strictly spherical.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] EPSG's definition says the projection "uses spherical development of ellipsoidal coordinates".
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The underlying geographic coordinates are defined using the WGS84 ellipsoidal model of the Earth's surface, but are projected as if defined on a sphere.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] This practice is uncontroversial for small-scale maps (such as of the entire world), but has little precedent in large-scale maps (such as of a city or province).
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The ellipsoidal Mercator has these same properties, but models the earth as an ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Unlike the ellipsoidal Mercator, however, the Web Mercator is not quite conformal.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] This means that angles between lines on the surface will not be drawn to the same angles in the map, although they will not deviate enough to be noticeable by eye.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Lines deviate because Web Mercator specifies that coordinates be given as surveyed on the WGS 84 ellipsoidal model.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] By projecting coordinates surveyed against the ellipsoid as if they were surveyed on a sphere, angular relationships change slightly.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The benefit the Web Mercator gains is that the spherical form is much simpler to calculate than the ellipsoidal form, and so requires only a fraction of the computing resources.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Due to slow adoption by the EPSG registry, the Web Mercator is represented by several different names and spatial reference system identifiers (SRIDs), including EPSG:900913, EPSG:3785 and EPSG:3857, the latter being the official EPSG identifier since 2008.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] We will not devalue the EPSG dataset by including such inappropriate geodesy and cartography." The unofficial code "EPSG:900913" (GOOGLE transliterated to numbers) came to be used.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] It was originally defined by Christopher Schmidt in his Technical Ramblings blog and became codified in OpenLayers 2, which, technically, would make OpenLayers the SRID authority.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] In 2008, EPSG provided the official identifier EPSG:3785 with the official name "Popular Visualisation CRS / Mercator", but noted "It is not an official geodetic system".
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] This definition used a spherical (rather than ellipsoidal) model of the Earth.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Later that year, EPSG provided an updated identifier, EPSG:3857 with the official name "WGS 84 / Pseudo-Mercator".
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The definition switched to using the WGS84 ellipsoid (EPSG:4326), rather than the sphere.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Although the projection is closely associated with Google, Microsoft is listed as the "information source" in EPSG's standards.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] Other identifiers that have been used include ESRI:102113, ESRI:102100, and OSGEO:41001.
[src:map-projections/web-mercator-projection] The projection covers the Earth from −180° to 180° longitude, and 85.05° north and south.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The **World Geodetic System** (**WGS**) is a standard used in cartography, geodesy, and satellite navigation including GPS.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The current version, **WGS 84**, defines an Earth-centered, Earth-fixed coordinate system and a geodetic datum, and also describes the associated Earth Gravitational Model (EGM) and World Magnetic Model (WMM).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The standard is published and maintained by the United States National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Efforts to supplement the various national surveying systems began in the 19th century with F.R.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Helmert's book *Mathematische und Physikalische Theorien der Physikalischen Geodäsie* (*Mathematical and Physical Theories of Physical Geodesy*).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Austria and Germany founded the *Zentralbüro für die Internationale Erdmessung* (Central Bureau of International Geodesy), and a series of global ellipsoids of the Earth were derived (e.g., Helmert 1906, Hayford 1910 and 1924).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] In the late 1950s, the United States Department of Defense, together with scientists of other institutions and countries, began to develop the needed world system to which geodetic data could be referred and compatibility established between the coordinates of widely separated sites of interest.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Army, Navy and Air Force were combined leading to the DoD World Geodetic System 1960 (WGS 60).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The term *datum* as used here refers to a smooth surface somewhat arbitrarily defined as zero elevation, consistent with a set of surveyor's measures of distances between various stations, and differences in elevation, all reduced to a grid of latitudes, longitudes, and elevations.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Heritage surveying methods found elevation differences from a local horizontal determined by the spirit level, plumb line, or an equivalent device that depends on the local gravity field (see physical geodesy).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] As a result, the elevations in the data are referenced to the geoid, a surface that is not readily found using satellite geodesy.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The latter observational method is more suitable for global mapping.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Therefore, a motivation, and a substantial problem in the WGS and similar work is to patch together data that were not only made separately, for different regions, but to re-reference the elevations to an ellipsoid model rather than to the geoid.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] In accomplishing WGS 60, a combination of available surface gravity data, astro-geodetic data and results from HIRAN and Canadian SHORAN surveys were used to define a best-fitting ellipsoid and an earth-centered orientation for each initially selected datum.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] (Every datum is relatively oriented with respect to different portions of the geoid by the astro-geodetic methods already described.) The sole contribution of satellite data to the development of WGS 60 was a value for the ellipsoid flattening which was obtained from the nodal motion of a satellite.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Air Force had each developed a world system by using different approaches to the gravimetric datum orientation method.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] To determine their gravimetric orientation parameters, the Air Force used the mean of the differences between the gravimetric and astro-geodetic deflections and geoid heights (undulations) at specifically selected stations in the areas of the major datums.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The Army performed an adjustment to minimize the difference between astro-geodetic and gravimetric geoids.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] By matching the relative astro-geodetic geoids of the selected datums with an earth-centered gravimetric geoid, the selected datums were reduced to an earth-centered orientation.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Since the Army and Air Force systems agreed remarkably well for the NAD, ED and TD areas, they were consolidated and became WGS 60.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Improvements to the global system included the Astrogeoid of Irene Fischer and the astronautic Mercury datum.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] In January 1966, a World Geodetic System Committee composed of representatives from the United States Army, Navy and Air Force was charged with developing an improved WGS, needed to satisfy mapping, charting and geodetic requirements.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Additional surface gravity observations, results from the extension of triangulation and trilateration networks, and large amounts of Doppler and optical satellite data had become available since the development of WGS 60.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Using the additional data and improved techniques, WGS 66 was produced which served DoD needs for about five years after its implementation in 1967.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The defining parameters of the WGS 66 Ellipsoid were the flattening (1⁄298.25 determined from satellite data) and the semimajor axis (6378145 m determined from a combination of Doppler satellite and astro-geodetic data).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] A worldwide 5° × 5° mean free air gravity anomaly field provided the basic data for producing the WGS 66 gravimetric geoid.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Also, a geoid referenced to the WGS 66 Ellipsoid was derived from available astrogeodetic data to provide a detailed representation of limited land areas.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] After an extensive effort over a period of approximately three years, the Department of Defense World Geodetic System 1972 was completed.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Selected satellite, surface gravity and astrogeodetic data available through 1972 from both DoD and non-DoD sources were used in a Unified WGS Solution (a large scale least squares adjustment).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The results of the adjustment consisted of corrections to initial station coordinates and coefficients of the gravitational field.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The largest collection of data ever used for WGS purposes was assembled, processed and applied in the development of WGS 72.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Both optical and electronic satellite data were used.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The electronic satellite data consisted, in part, of Doppler data provided by the U.S.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Navy and cooperating non-DoD satellite tracking stations established in support of the Navy's Navigational Satellite System (NNSS).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Doppler data was also available from the numerous sites established by GEOCEIVERS during 1971 and 1972.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Doppler data was the primary data source for WGS 72 (see image).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Additional electronic satellite data was provided by the SECOR (Sequential Collation of Range) Equatorial Network completed by the U.S.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Optical satellite data from the Worldwide Geometric Satellite Triangulation Program was provided by the BC-4 camera system (see image).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Data from the Smithsonian Astrophysical Observatory was also used which included camera (Baker–Nunn) and some laser ranging.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The surface gravity field used in the Unified WGS Solution consisted of a set of 410 10° × 10° equal area mean free air gravity anomalies determined solely from terrestrial data.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] This gravity field includes mean anomaly values compiled directly from observed gravity data wherever the latter was available in sufficient quantity.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The value for areas of sparse or no observational data were developed from geophysically compatible gravity approximations using gravity-geophysical correlation techniques.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Approximately 45 percent of the 410 mean free air gravity anomaly values were determined directly from observed gravity data.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The astrogeodetic data in its basic form consists of deflection of the vertical components referred to the various national geodetic datums.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] These deflection values were integrated into astrogeodetic geoid charts referred to these national datums.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The geoid heights contributed to the Unified WGS Solution by providing additional and more detailed data for land areas.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Conventional ground survey data was included in the solution to enforce a consistent adjustment of the coordinates of neighboring observation sites of the BC-4, SECOR, Doppler and Baker–Nunn systems.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Also, eight geodimeter long line precise traverses were included for the purpose of controlling the scale of the solution.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The Unified WGS Solution, as stated above, was a solution for geodetic positions and associated parameters of the gravitational field based on an optimum combination of available data.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The WGS 72 ellipsoid parameters, datum shifts and other associated constants were derived separately.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] For the unified solution, a normal equation matrix was formed based on each of the mentioned data sets.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Then, the individual normal equation matrices were combined and the resultant matrix solved to obtain the positions and the parameters.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The value for the semimajor axis (a) of the WGS 72 Ellipsoid is 6378135 m.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The adoption of an a-value 10 meters smaller than that for the WGS 66 Ellipsoid was based on several calculations and indicators including a combination of satellite and surface gravity data for position and gravitational field determinations.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Sets of satellite derived station coordinates and gravimetric deflection of the vertical and geoid height data were used to determine local-to-geocentric datum shifts, datum rotation parameters, a datum scale parameter and a value for the semimajor axis of the WGS Ellipsoid.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Eight solutions were made with the various sets of input data, both from an investigative point of view and also because of the limited number of unknowns which could be solved for in any individual solution due to computer limitations.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Selected Doppler satellite tracking and astro-geodetic datum orientation stations were included in the various solutions.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Based on these results and other related studies accomplished by the committee, an a-value of 6378135 m and a flattening of 1/298.26 were adopted.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] In the development of local-to WGS 72 datum shifts, results from different geodetic disciplines were investigated, analyzed and compared.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Those shifts adopted were based primarily on a large number of Doppler TRANET and GEOCEIVER station coordinates which were available worldwide.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] These coordinates had been determined using the Doppler point positioning method.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] In the early 1980s, the need for a new world geodetic system was generally recognized by the geodetic community as well as within the US Department of Defense.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] WGS 72 no longer provided sufficient data, information, geographic coverage, or product accuracy for all then-current and anticipated applications.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The means for producing a new WGS were available in the form of improved data, increased data coverage, new data types and improved techniques.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Observations from Doppler, satellite laser ranging and very-long-baseline interferometry (VLBI) constituted significant new information.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] An outstanding new source of data had become available from satellite radar altimetry.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Also available was an advanced least squares method called collocation that allowed for a consistent combination solution from different types of measurements all relative to the Earth's gravity field, measurements such as the geoid, gravity anomalies, deflections, and dynamic Doppler.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The new world geodetic system was called WGS 84.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] It is the reference system used by the Global Positioning System.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] It is geocentric and globally consistent within 1 m.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Current geodetic realizations of the geocentric reference system family International Terrestrial Reference System (ITRS) maintained by the IERS are geocentric, and internally consistent, at the few-cm level, while still being metre-level consistent with WGS 84.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The WGS 84 reference ellipsoid was based on GRS 80, but it contains a very slight variation in the inverse flattening, as it was derived independently and the result was rounded to a different number of significant digits.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] This resulted in a tiny difference of 0.105 mm in the semi-minor axis.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The following table compares the primary ellipsoid parameters.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The coordinate origin of WGS 84 is meant to be located at the Earth's center of mass; the uncertainty is believed to be less than 2 cm.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The WGS 84 meridian of zero longitude is the IERS Reference Meridian, 5.3 arc seconds or 102 metres (335 ft) east of the Greenwich meridian at the latitude of the Royal Observatory.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The WGS 84 datum surface is an oblate spheroid with equatorial radius a = 6378137 m at the equator and flattening f = 1⁄298.257223563.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The refined value of the WGS 84 gravitational constant (mass of Earth's atmosphere included) is GM = 3.986004418×1014 m3/s2.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The angular velocity of the Earth is defined to be ω = 72.92115×10−6 rad/s.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] This leads to several computed parameters such as the polar semi-minor axis b which equals *a* × (1 − *f*) = 6356752.3142 m, and the first eccentricity squared, *e*2 = 6.69437999014×10−3.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The original standardization document for WGS 84 was Technical Report 8350.2, published in September 1987 by the Defense Mapping Agency (which later became the National Imagery and Mapping Agency).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] New editions were published in September 1991 and July 1997; the latter edition was amended twice, in January 2000 and June 2004.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The standardization document was revised again and published in July 2014 by the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency as NGA.STND.0036.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] These updates provide refined descriptions of the Earth and realizations of the system for higher precision.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The original WGS84 model had an absolute accuracy of 1–2 meters.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] WGS84 (G730) first incorporated GPS observations, taking the accuracy down to 10 cm/component rms.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] All following revisions including WGS84 (G873) and WGS84 (G1150) also used GPS.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] WGS 84 (G1762) is the sixth update to the WGS reference frame.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] WGS 84 has most recently been updated to use the reference frame **G2296**, which was released on 7 January 2024 as an update to G2139, now aligned to both the ITRF2020, the most recent ITRF realization, and the IGS20, the frame used by the International GNSS Service (IGS).
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] G2139 was aligned with the IGb14 realization of the International Terrestrial Reference Frame (ITRF) 2014 and uses the new IGS Antex standard.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Updates to the original geoid for WGS 84 are now published as a separate Earth Gravitational Model (EGM), with improved resolution and accuracy.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Likewise, the World Magnetic Model (WMM) is updated separately.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] The current version of WGS 84 uses EGM2008 and WMM2025.
[src:map-projections/world-geodetic-system] Solution for Earth orientation parameters consistent with ITRF2014 is also needed (IERS EOP 14C04).
